<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06278249 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06278249 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; Aristide speaks at the U.N.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PAST; PRESIDENT; HAITI; REACTION; GOVERNMENT; CHANGE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Speaking from his heart, Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide appealed tothe world for help in ousting the army mutineers who seized power and to stopthe massacre in his homeland.;   As Aristide strode into the Security Councilchambers Thursday night, diplomats and observers in the gallery rose silentlyin respect.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  'HOW MANY MORE?' OUSTED LEADER ASKS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related story on P. 4A of this section  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;I see the peace-loving people that I have known go before me, before mymind, and I know they have died,&quot; he told the ambassadors as he gazed intotheir eyes and spoke without notes.;   &quot;How many more will be massacred if anend is not put, once and for all, to this attempt to murder democracy?&quot; theformer leftist priest said.;   &quot;Military boots are always ready to crush apeople who are trying to stake their lives and live peaceably for democracy,&quot;Aristide said in French, speaking through a translator. &quot;This threat todemocracy in Haiti also constitutes a threat to democracy everywhere,throughout the world.&quot;;   He left the council chambers to a brief standingovation.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  United Nations  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911004  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  188  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, October 4, 199100278249,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </